entry.title: Austracantha minax
entry.content: On its web in my Mum’s front garden.

entry.title: Abantiades labyrinthicus
entry.content: Trapped by accident in my concertina fly wire. Seen here resting after release. Thanks to Cathy Powers and Chris Lindorff for id.

entry.title: Alisterus scapularis
entry.content: One of two King parrots that visited this morning. They liked the Olearias. Very comfortable with us, seemed very used to people.

entry.title: Arthropodium strictum s.s.
entry.content: Swathes of chocolate lilies along the edge of Barrm Birrm. Photo taken via Facebook messenger and does NOT do the displays justice in any way.

entry.title: Hardenbergia violacea
entry.content: A small spray resting on the hillside of the dam in Barrm Birrm.

entry.title: Cacatua sanguinea/tenuirostris
entry.content: Thrilled to observe a corella sitting on the edge of his/her hole in the tree trunk.

entry.title: Triglochin spp.
entry.content: A full and flowing Riddells Creek is always a joy to behold. A mix of water ribbons and the South African water lily (?) could be seen. Using Facebook messenger camera!

entry.title: Chenonetta jubata
entry.content: I assume these are Wood ducks. An unusual sight at our place. We ha e an ephemeral creek so I assume they are around because of recent rains livening up the creek. Seen here on top of where our resident wombat has been digging.

entry.title: Vombatus ursinus
entry.content: Photo taken from inside the car using Facebook Messenger camera in pitch black and howling gale! It's the record that counts!

entry.title: Wallabia bicolor
entry.content: A poor photo taken through the front window of the house using Facebook Messenger camera! Wallaby seen eating the fallen leaves from the flowering cherry tree.

entry.title: Macropus giganteus
entry.content: A handsome visitor this morning.

entry.title: Vombatus ursinus
entry.content: Seen on side of road eating grass. Shocking photo but great to see. Over the last two years I have keep seen wombats where I've never seen them before.

entry.title: Galenia pubescens var. pubescens
entry.content: Between the Wohl Court signpost and the white post on the south side of the road.

entry.title: Rhipidura albiscapa
entry.content: Enjoying what little water is around.

entry.title: Rhipidura rufifrons
entry.content: Taken with iPhone. Very flighty, very beautiful.

entry.title: Blechnum spp.
entry.content: In steep cliff face Bullengarook slate mine area. Currently very dry but ferns hanging on.

entry.title: Hemianax papuensis, Odonata spp.
entry.content: Ellena Best spotted this dragonfly on a grapevine in the main street of Stratford. She also took the photo.

entry.title: Arctocephalus pusillus
entry.content: Basking under the tourist information caravan in Mallacoota. We saw him move off into the water.

entry.title: Tachyglossus aculeatus
entry.content: On opposite side of road to our house.

entry.title: Chlorocoma dichloraria
entry.content: Inside house on bedroom wall. ID by Chris Lindorff and Cathy Powers.

entry.title: Chenonetta jubata
entry.content: This was part of one family of two families on Whitakers Lane Riddells Creek. Seems to be a bumper year.

entry.title: Phascolarctos cinereus
entry.content: A koala in a tree at 410 Gap Road. We hear and see them frequently here. This one gave us a great display of his stretched out neck while grunting.

entry.title: Cervus spp.
entry.content: Three deer spotted by Steve Best on our hill. The first sighting on our property. Oh dear.

entry.title: Strepera graculina
entry.content: This Currawong was seriously upsetting a new holland honeyeater.

entry.title: Macropus giganteus
entry.content: Watched for some time two kangaroos fighting. They were impressive looking animals. Tall and strong. The Kangaroos around them seemed to take little notice.

entry.title: Dacelo novaeguineae
entry.content: Two kookaburras on the washing line. I'm used to seeing one sitting there but lovely to see two.

entry.title: Alisterus scapularis
entry.content: Ellena Best aged 10 exclaimed "Hey Mum there's a King Parrot!" And sure enough. It is the first time a King Parrot has been recorded on our property. It flew down to the deck and sat on a pole and then sat on the water heater. Its distinctive call could be heard in the surrounding forest.

entry.title: Cymbonotus preissianus
entry.content: New species record for this collection. Found in the area burnt in last year's January wildfire.

entry.title: Vombatus ursinus
entry.content: This wombat photo was captured on a night camera. The first official record of a wombat here!

entry.title: Cervus dama
entry.content: Seen crossing Gap Rd into Barrm Birrm late afternoon. Showed little fear.

entry.title: Petroica boodang
entry.content: Seen flying around back garden for three days. Too flighty for me to take a photograph!

entry.title: Vombatus ursinus
entry.content: Young wombat seen crossing road from farm.

entry.title: Tachyglossus aculeatus
entry.content: Spotted and photographed by Lydia Best (aged 12).

entry.title: Canis lupus dingo
entry.content: Down in the gully north east of Mount Nelse we heard howling noises that we think were dingoes.

entry.title: Eulamprus spp.
entry.content: Ellena Best (age 10) found and photographed these two water skinks between two rocks by the Watchbed creek.

entry.title: Tachyglossus aculeatus
entry.content: On side of road.

entry.title: Phalaenoides glycinae
entry.content: Found by Alice Cummins on pavement outside shops at High St, Woodend. Identified by Chris Lindorff.

entry.title: Cervus dama
entry.content: Towards top of Shannon's Road.

entry.title: Wallabia bicolor
entry.content: Two swamp wallabies showing amazing colour differences.

entry.title: Eucalyptus pauciflora subsp. acerina
entry.content: One of many stunning specimens on Mt St. Gwinear.

entry.title: Amphibolurus muricatus
entry.content: Spotted initially by Ellena Best near bottom of Mount Zero, the Grampians.

entry.title: Tachyglossus aculeatus
entry.content: Observed at bottom of garden near creek but daughter Ellena said she first saw it tumble down the slope!

entry.title: Poecilometis spp.
entry.content: This fell on my Mum's, Pam Brooks, head as she walked outside from the laundry.

entry.title: Tachyglossus aculeatus
entry.content: In front garden.

entry.title: Vombatus ursinus
entry.content: Crossed Shannons Rd into the bush. Not a large wombat, looked quite young.

entry.title: Vombatus ursinus
entry.content: Small, seemed young. Crossed from our property across the dirt road into the bush.

entry.title: Tiliqua rugosa
entry.content: I stood on this stumpy tail as I got out of the car. Thankfully unharmed.

entry.title: Caedicia simplex
entry.content: Found with two others in a Grevillea georgiana.

entry.title: Papilio aegeus aegeus
entry.content: Orchard swallowtail seen flying quickly around a variety of trees and plants. Never settled to be able to take a photograph.
